{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The conversation history passed to the LLM is trimmed to the most recent 10 messages when the full history exceeds the context window.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The failure boundary is prompt-construction logic (list slicing/order), which is local and deterministic. No real I/O, subprocess, or model behavior is required to expose an off-by-one/order bug.","test_description":"Unit-test the history-trimming function with >10 messages and assert exactly the latest 10 are included, in correct chronological order, and that <=10 messages are unchanged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.82,"Integration":0.16,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The generated response addresses the customer's question rather than producing a generic or off-topic reply.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real LLM output quality and non-determinism. A mocked model can easily hide relevance failures by always returning a canned 'good' answer.","test_description":"Run prompt-response tests against the real production model on a small set of representative customer questions; score relevance (rubric or human/LLM-as-judge with thresholds) and fail if responses are generic/off-topic beyond allowed rate.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The tone re-check correctly identifies when a response is too formal for a casual-tier customer and triggers regeneration.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"The key failure is tone classification correctness, which is semantic and model-dependent. If that check is mocked, misclassification risk is hidden. Regeneration trigger can be asserted in the same test run once real tone judgment is exercised.","test_description":"Use real tone-check (or real LLM-based tone evaluator) with intentionally formal draft responses for casual-tier inputs; assert the response is flagged and regeneration path is invoked.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.64,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full exchange (user message, generated response, any regenerations) is persisted to the database with correct timestamps.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This failure appears at module boundaries: chatbot orchestration + persistence layer + clock/timestamp mapping. A unit test of a repository method alone can miss schema/transaction/wiring issues.","test_description":"Run an integration test with a real test database (local container or ephemeral DB), execute a conversation that includes regeneration, then verify all records are written with expected fields and monotonic/correct timestamps.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.84,"System":0.09,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the tone check triggers regeneration, the second response replaces the first — the customer never sees the rejected draft.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is orchestration/state handoff behavior across generation, tone-check, and response-delivery modules. The real failure is wiring/order-of-operations, not model quality itself.","test_description":"Integration-test the request pipeline with deterministic stubbed LLM outputs (first bad-tone, second acceptable) and assert delivered customer payload contains only the second response while internal logs retain both drafts.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}}]}
